cs.CV, cs.RO, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.GR 

This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it proposes a vision system that utilizes a low-cost monocular RGB camera to acquire accurate depth estimation for robotic applications. Additionally, the paper mentions experiments on the Middlebury dataset, which is a well-known benchmark for stereo vision algorithms. 

The paper also mentions the use of a robot arm to capture a sequence of images, indicating that it may also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. 

The proposed system involves combining cost volumes for stereo matching, which suggests that it may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The paper mentions the use of a fused cost volume that is robust to outliers, indicating that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper involves the use of computer graphics techniques to generate multiscopic vision, suggesting that it may also belong to the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category.
